<TITLE> Rivers swell after torrential rains </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 3 (bdnews24.com)Torrential rains and onrush of waters downhill from India have swelled rivers in many districts. As the rivers are rising, so is erosion of banks. Lowlands in Feni, Sunamganj and Kurigram among other places were flooded on Friday, stranding thousands. In Kurigram, water has been rising in 16 rivers that flooded over 25 villages. Some 10,000 people are already marooned. Water Development Board recorded 13cm water rise in the Dhorala, 17cm in the Dudhkumor and 32 cm in the Bramhaputra. In Sunamganj, rivers flooded lowlands in five upazilas. Waters of the Surma was flowing 48cm over the danger mark on Friday noon at Shologhar point and 85mm rainfall was recorded in the last 24 hours, marooning 'thousands' in five upazilas, say local officials. In Nilphamari, the Teesta, flowing 15cm over the danger level, has flooded seven villages in three unions and left 1,500 people stranded. In Feni, eight villages of Phulgazi and Porshuram upazilas were flooded as water of the Muhuri was flowing more than 80cm over the usual mark. In Lalmonirhat, the flood situation in Hatibandha and Kaliganj upazilas worsened. Thousands of acres of land were flooded and 6,000 people marooned, by local estimates. bdnew
